Weekly Sales Prediction: A Comparison of Classical ML Methods

The main objective of this project is to predict the Sales numeric label for a hidden test set, with a dataset that have weekly instances. For it, we will restrain ourselves to "classical" Machine Learning methods due to the lack of training data (not neural networks, although a simple one was tested). For achieving this, we define two secondary objectives:

  • Preprocessing: find the best preprocessing of the data (EDA, understand the relationships between the features, do feature engineering that improves the performance).
  • Best model: with an adequate train-validation split, find the best model and do the predictions for the hidden test set.

Furthermore, a key part of the project are the insights, that will help us understand which features are the most related to the sales and how, so it can help in making future decisions.

In this notebook every step of the work is detailed. After the setup, an Exploratory Data Analysis is performed to fully understand the dataset and the relationships between features. With that information, the preprocessing of the data is done, doing key feature engineering for the performance of the future models. Before the creation of the models, more dataset insights are extracted thanks to a statistical analysis and the evaluation method for selecting the best model is explained. Finally, all the models are trained and evaluated, extracting information about the data with each one of them, and the final predictions and conclusions are detailed.

Add month and year columns

Date variable: OHE with LOO

For our Monday_date variable, we are going to apply One Hot Enconding with Leave-One-Out regularization.

In[21]:
full_dataset['Week_Number'] = full_dataset['Monday_date'].dt.isocalendar().week
In[22]:
def calculate_sales_in_week(row):
    
    week_sales = full_dataset[full_dataset['Week_Number'] == row['Week_Number']]['Sales']
    week_sales = week_sales[week_sales.index != row.name]  # Exclude the current row
    return week_sales.mean()

full_dataset['Week_Sales'] = full_dataset.apply(calculate_sales_in_week, axis=1)

It is just a stat that reflects the sales for that week from another years, something that a business can easily calculate.

Key aspects of the correlations between features:

  • Stores is highly correlated to Monday_date, which means that its value is very dependent on it. This features probably represents the number of total stores opened (with the pass of the time, more stores open). However, this does not give any predictive value (as we can see watching its correlation with Sales) so we will drop this feature for the models.

  • Most of the investment variables have been decreasing with date, with the only exception of TV_hbtv_investment, which have been increasing.

  • These are the investment variables ordered from bigger correlation with Sales to lower:

    1. TV_hbtv_investment: 0.5
    2. TV_investment: 0.4
    3. Meta_investment, sea_other_investment: 0.3
    4. Radio_investment: 0.2
    5. Affiliates_investment, tiktok_investment, Database_investment, OOH_investment: 0.1

A simple correlation analysis can show us how the different inversions in investments are helping with sales, with the most valuable being the ones related to TV (classic TV and hybrid TV). Investment in some online platforms like Meta (Facebook) or search engine advertising (SEA) are also correlated. Then, we have the rest of the investments, that show a low but non-zero correlation. This simple tool could be very useful for knowing how to invest in the future for the business.

F-Test (ANOVA) and Mutual Info Regression

Now, we are going to run two more complex tests for determining the relationship between Sales and the rest of the investment features. They will be an F-test based on an ANOVA (Analysis of Variance) model and, to capture non-linear relationships, we will also estimate the mutual information between them.

In[30]:
f_scores, p_values = f_regression(X, y)
mutual_info_scores = mutual_info_regression(X, y, random_state=0)

info_tests = pd.DataFrame({
    'Feature': X.columns,
    'F-Statistic': f_scores,
    'P-Value': p_values,
    'Mutual Information': mutual_info_scores
})

# Format
info_tests['F-Statistic'] = info_tests['F-Statistic'].round(3)
info_tests['P-Value'] = info_tests['P-Value'].apply(lambda x: f"{x:.2e}")
info_tests['Mutual Information'] = info_tests['Mutual Information'].round(3)

Evaluation Method

For comparing each of the models that we are going to try and for hyper-parameter optimization, we are going to follow this steps:

  1. Holdout (outer evaluation): Split data into train and test with 80-20%.
  2. Cross-Validation (inner evaluation): For each model, tune the HPs (HPO) with 10-fold CV using Optuna. Store MAE, params and time elapsed.
  3. Compare models using MAE.
  4. Select the best model and use it with the test data (not the prediction data) for performance evaluation.
  5. Final model: do HPO for that model using all the data.

Models

Now that we have defined all the steps and we have our data ready, we are going to introduce several models to predict the Sales variable. We are going to train models in order of complexity, as simpler models are more interpretable, giving us more insights into our data, while more complex models have a higher predicting power (while being less interpretable).

Dummy model

The first model will be a dummy model, as this will set the "worst" MAE possible so we can compare the rest of the models to it. As the objective is to minimize the MAE, the strategy will be set to 'median', which minimizes it.

Significant predictors ($p<0.05$):

  1. GBP:

    • $p < 0.001$
    • Interpretation: as GBP is probably related to some expenditure, this means that expending more leads to more sales. One-unit increase in GBP -> 0.1985 increase in Sales.

  2. TV_hbtv_investment:

    • p-value: < 0.001

  3. Week_Sales:

    • p-value: < 0.001
    • Interpretation: This was the variable introduced in the preprocessing step, which is very linearly correlated to the response. This shows how seasonality is very relevant to predicting sales. One-unit increase in Week_Sales -> 0.5585 increase in Sales.

  4. Database_investment:

    • p-value: 0.035
    • Interpretation: This investment also appears to be linearly correlated to the response, although it is less relevant than the previous variables, as one-unit increase in Database_investment -> 0.0275 decrease in Sales.

From the $R^2$ we see that the models fits reasonably well, with some significant predictors accounting for the response. However, most of the features are non-significant. Does this means that these four predictors are the only relevant? No, as there can be non-linear relationships. However, this model helps us understand the key aspects for the business if they want to increase sales:

  • Investing more money (if GBP is related to investment)
  • Invest money in hybrid TV advertising (TV_hbtv_investment)
  • Taking into account seasonality
  • Invest some money in database (maintenance, development, advertising...)

Before training more advanced models, we are going to build upon linear regression to see if it can get better results.

# Correlation matrix
correlation_matrix = investment_data.corr()

# Find highly correlated features
threshold = 0.5  # threshold
high_correlation_pairs = [
    (col1, col2)
    for col1, col2 in combinations(investment_columns, 2)
    if abs(correlation_matrix.loc[col1, col2]) > threshold
]

# Create interaction terms
interactions = pd.DataFrame(index=data.index)

Linear Regression with PCA

As adding feature interaction did not work and many of the predictors do not seem to be very relevant, we are going to check if linear regression gets better with dimensionality reduction. For it, we will introduce PCA into a pipeline and optimize the number of components to select:

In[50]:
def objective(trial):
    
    n_components = trial.suggest_int("n_components", 1, min(X_train.shape[1], X_train.shape[0] - 1))

    pc_regressor = Pipeline([
        ('scaler', StandardScaler()), 
        ('pca', PCA(n_components=n_components)),
        ('ridge', Ridge(random_state=RANDOM_SEED))
    ])
    
    inner_score = cross_val_score(pc_regressor, X_train, y_train, cv=inner, scoring='neg_mean_absolute_error').mean()
    mean_mae = - inner_score
    
    return mean_mae

study = optuna.create_study(direction='minimize', sampler=optuna.samplers.TPESampler(seed=RANDOM_SEED))
start_time = time.time()
study.optimize(objective, n_trials=20)

pc_metrics['Method'] = 'Linear Regression with PCA'
pc_metrics['MAE'] = study.best_value
pc_metrics['Params'] = study.best_params
pc_metrics['Time'] = time.time() - start_time

print("Best MAE:", pc_metrics['MAE'])
print("Best Parameters:", pc_metrics['Params'])
print(f"Time elapsed: {pc_metrics['Time']:.2f} s")

Best MAE: 277.60612645454535
Best Parameters: {'n_components': 9}
Time elapsed: 0.39 s

PCA seems to help a bit in the linear regression, probably because, as we said, many features are not relevant, but the difference is not significant.

Ridge Regression

Now we will introduce Ridge and Lasso regression, linear regression models with regularization techniches. In Ridge regression, the penalty of the loss function is proportional to the square of the coefficients.

Decision Tree

The first "advanced" model that we are going to test is a simple Decision Tree, which still retains some interpretation and it does not have high complexity. As always, we will optimize the most important parameters with Optuna:

In[54]:
def objective(trial):
    
    params = {
        "criterion": trial.suggest_categorical("criterion", ["squared_error", "friedman_mse", "absolute_error", "poisson"]),
        "splitter": trial.suggest_categorical("splitter", ["best", "random"]),
        "max_depth": trial.suggest_int("max_depth", 2, 20),
        "min_samples_split": trial.suggest_int("min_samples_split", 2, 20),
        "min_samples_leaf": trial.suggest_int("min_samples_leaf", 1, 20),
        "max_features": trial.suggest_categorical("max_features", [None, "sqrt", "log2"]),
    }

    dt_regressor = DecisionTreeRegressor(random_state=RANDOM_SEED, **params)
    
    inner_score = cross_val_score(dt_regressor, X_train, y_train, cv=inner, scoring='neg_mean_absolute_error').mean()

    return mean_mae

It shows worse performance than linear regression models, so we will try to improve its prediction capabilities with more complex models (ensemble models) next. However, we can fit the Decision Tree with the best parameters obtained to the train data to see how the tree looks, to get some insights about it.

In[55]:
dt_regressor = DecisionTreeRegressor(random_state=RANDOM_SEED, **dt_metrics['Params'])
dt_regressor.fit(X_train, y_train)

plt.figure(figsize=(20, 10))
plot_tree(dt_regressor, filled=True , feature_names=X.columns, precision=2)
plt.show()

The criterion used for the tree is absolute error, which may be has been influenced by the score being -MAE. The predictors used in each node are the ones that we have been seeing until now: Week_Sales, TV_investment, TV_hbtv_investment, Radio_investment and GBP; so here they are showing its relevance for the response Sales.

The first node, and the one that minimizes the mean absolute error, is based on Week_Sales: we could interpret this split as being in peak season (before holidays, for example) or not. Then, the investment variables are used to split more nodes and, although there are just 7 final nodes (it is a simple model), the MAE is good compared to the model that we have seen until now.

Random Forest

Now that we have seen the possibilities of a single Decision Tree, we are going to train some ensemble models of them. The first of them will be a Random Forest:

In[56]:
def objective(trial):
    
    params = {
        "n_estimators": trial.suggest_int("n_estimators", 10, 200),
        "max_depth": trial.suggest_int("max_depth", 2, 20),
        "min_samples_split": trial.suggest_int("min_samples_split", 2, 20),
        "min_samples_leaf": trial.suggest_int("min_samples_leaf", 1, 10),
        "max_features": trial.suggest_categorical("max_features", [None, "sqrt", "log2"]),
        "bootstrap": trial.suggest_categorical("bootstrap", [True, False]),
    }

    rf_regressor = RandomForestRegressor(random_state=RANDOM_SEED, **params)
    
    inner_score = cross_val_score(rf_regressor, X_train, y_train, cv=inner, scoring='neg_mean_absolute_error').mean()
    mean_mae = - inner_score
    
    return mean_mae

study = optuna.create_study(direction='minimize', sampler=optuna.samplers.TPESampler(seed=RANDOM_SEED))

Neural Network: Multi-Layer Perceptron

The final model that we are going to test is the most complex until now: a multi-layer perceptron. The number of hidden layers (l) and the number of elements in each one of them will be optimized, together with activation (as we saw in the slides) and alpha.

In[60]:
def objective(trial):
    
    l = trial.suggest_int("l", 1, 6)

    params = {
        "hidden_layer_sizes": tuple(trial.suggest_int(f"element_{i}", 2, 30) for i in range(l)),
        "activation": trial.suggest_categorical("activation", ["identity", "logistic", "tanh", "relu"]),
        #"solver": trial.suggest_categorical("solver", ["adam", "sgd"]),
        "alpha": trial.suggest_float("alpha", 1e-5, 1e-1, log=True),
        #"learning_rate": trial.suggest_categorical("learning_rate", ["constant", "invscaling", "adaptive"]),
        #"learning_rate_init": trial.suggest_float("learning_rate_init", 1e-5, 1e-1, log=True),
        #"batch_size": trial.suggest_categorical("batch_size", [32, 64, 128])
    }

    nn_regressor = Pipeline([
        ('scaler', StandardScaler()), # Scaling is important for MLPRegressor
        ('regressor', MLPRegressor(random_state=RANDOM_SEED, max_iter=20000, **params))
    ])
    
    inner_score = cross_val_score(nn_regressor, X_train, y_train, cv=inner, scoring='neg_mean_absolute_error').mean()
    mean_mae = - inner_score
    
    return mean_mae

study = optuna.create_study(direction='minimize', sampler=optuna.samplers.TPESampler(seed=RANDOM_SEED))
start_time = time.time()
study.optimize(objective, n_trials=3000)

nn_metrics['Method'] = 'Neural Network'
nn_metrics['MAE'] = study.best_value
nn_metrics['Params'] = study.best_params
nn_metrics['Time'] = time.time() - start_time

print("Best MAE:", nn_metrics['MAE'])
print("Best Parameters:", nn_metrics['Params'])
print(f"Time elapsed: {nn_metrics['Time']:.2f} s")

Best MAE: 280.56079922986873
Best Parameters: {'l': 5, 'element_0': 30, 'element_1': 29, 'element_2': 20, 'element_3': 30, 'element_4': 24, 'activation': 'identity', 'alpha': 0.02751477064246737}

The time taken for optimizing it was huge, and the final performance is not better than the rest of the models. HPO with the whole dataset

In[66]:
def objective(trial):
    
    params = {
        "n_estimators": trial.suggest_int("n_estimators", 50, 200),
        "learning_rate": trial.suggest_float("learning_rate", 0.001, 0.2, log=True),
        "max_depth": trial.suggest_int("max_depth", 2, 20),
        "min_samples_split": trial.suggest_int("min_samples_split", 2, 20),
        "min_samples_leaf": trial.suggest_int("min_samples_leaf", 1, 10),
        "subsample": trial.suggest_float("subsample", 0.5, 1.0),
        "max_features": trial.suggest_categorical("max_features", [None, "sqrt", "log2"]),
    }

    final_regressor = GradientBoostingRegressor(random_state=RANDOM_SEED, **params)
    
    inner_score = cross_val_score(final_regressor, X, y, cv=inner, scoring='neg_mean_absolute_error').mean()
    mean_mae = - inner_score
    
    return mean_mae

study = optuna.create_study(direction='minimize', sampler=optuna.samplers.TPESampler(seed=RANDOM_SEED))

Insights

Finally, with this final model that we have obtained, we will obtaine some final insights. During all the project we have been learning about our predictors (focusing on the investment variables). Now, we are going to study how our definitive and best model treats the features.

Feature Importances

From GradientBoostingRegressor we can extract the feature importances, which are computed based on the total reduction of impurity (in our case, Friedman MSE, as this method only allows this criterion and MSE).

In[71]:
# Get feature importances
feature_importances = final_regressor.feature_importances_

# Sort and plot
indices = np.argsort(feature_importances)[::-1]
plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6))
plt.bar(range(len(feature_importances)), feature_importances[indices], align="center")
plt.xticks(range(len(feature_importances)), np.array(predictors)[indices], rotation=90)
plt.title("Feature Importances")
plt.show()

The order of importance is similar to what we have been seeing until now, with TV_invesment (not TV_hbtv_investment) being the most relevant investment feature. However, it is interesting that the most important feature for this final model is nor Week_Sales as in the previous ones (although it is very near): it is GBP. As this feature is related to some money quantity (for example, some investment), it is very relevant for the business that Sales depend quite a lot on it.

The rest of the predictors were also used by the model, only that in a smaller degree. Other interesing non-investment predictors are web_visits and sea_brand, which were quite useful for the model.

Partial Dependence Plots

For getting more information, apart from the feature importances, we can use PartialDependenceDisplay from sklearn to see the partial dependences for all the predictors, ordered by feature importance:

In[72]:
# Create partial dependence plots

We can check the form of the positive relationships between Sales and the non-invesment predictors GBP, Week_Sales and web_visits; and the more relevant investment predictors TV_investment, TV_hbtv_investment and Affiliates_investment. The other relationships are not as clearly positive and simple as that, showing how investment in these fields may not impact directly the number of Sales.

SHAP

SHAP (SHapley Additive exPlanations) is a popular framework for explaining general machine learning models predictions based in game theory (specifically, the Shapley value concept, which assigns a fair value to each predictor based on its contribution to the final outcome). This can provide a explanation of predictors relevance in a different way than the previous feature importance that we have done.

In[73]:
# Initialize the explainer
explainer = shap.Explainer(final_regressor, X)

# Calculate SHAP values
shap_values = explainer(X)

# Summary plot
shap.summary_plot(shap_values, X, feature_names=predictors)

Again, we see a similar order to all the previous analysis, which reinforces the insights that we have for the predictors relevance.

The model uses the relevant features the most, showing how splitting nodes with it can lead to final nodes with good prediction values.

Conclusions

Let's sum up the explanations regarding variables affecting Sales that we have learned along the project:

  • Investment-related variables: we have seen how some of the most relevant predictors were related to investment. However, their relevance was quite different between them, so we can order them by importance:

    1. Investment on TV: all the tools used revealed that the most important investment predictors were those related with TV: TV_investment and TV_hbtv_investment. The business should allocate most of its investments on them.

    2. Other relevant investments: Affiliates_invesment and Database_investment showed relevance also during the tests and the models. Although not as important as investment on TV, the business should not stop investing on these fields.

    3. Less relevant investments: the other investments showed some importance, but it was clearly smaller that the importance for the variables in points 1 and 2. Also, interaction between them did not appear to be relevant, so if the business needs to reduce its total investment, it should start cutting in these fields.

  • Non investment-related variables: although we were focusing on investment variables, other predictors have shown its importance for predicting sales, which gives the business information about the market:

    1. Seasonality: as we knew the date of the week for each number of sales during more than two years, we created the variable Week_Sales for taking into account seasonality. It turned out to be quite relevant, as sales during a week can be predicted partially if we know the data from other years.

    2. Relevant variables: GBP, web_visits and sea_brand have been significant during most of the models, so the business can gain more insights with these relationships.
